OAI-PMH¶

La documentación del protocolo la podéis encontrar aquí:

https://www.openarchives.org/OAI/openarchivesprotocol.html

Librerías necesarias para la práctica¶

import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import requests
import json
In [146]:
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import requests
import json

Identify¶

This verb is used to retrieve information about a repository. Some of the information returned is required as part of the OAI-PMH. Repositories may also employ the Identify verb to return additional descriptive information.

In [147]:
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import requests

# https://zenodo.org/oai2d + el verbo que quiero utiilzar

oai = requests.get('https://zenodo.org/oai2d?verb=Identify') #Peticion al servidor

#Para crear el arbol XML
xmlTree = ET.fromstring(oai.text)
print(oai.text)
print()

<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="/static/xsl/oai2.xsl"?>
<OAI-PMH xmlns="http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/ http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/OAI-PMH.xsd">
  <responseDate>2019-12-27T22:24:12Z</responseDate>
  <request verb="Identify">https://zenodo.org/oai2d</request>
  <Identify>
    <repositoryName>Zenodo</repositoryName>
    <baseURL>https://zenodo.org/oai2d</baseURL>
    <protocolVersion>2.0</protocolVersion>
    <adminEmail>info@zenodo.org</adminEmail>
    <earliestDatestamp>2014-02-03T14:41:33Z</earliestDatestamp>
    <deletedRecord>no</deletedRecord>
    <granularity>YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ssZ</granularity>
  </Identify>
</OAI-PMH>
In [148]:
#Iterator para recorrer todos los elementos (incluso anidados)
iterator = xmlTree.iter()
for elem in iterator:
    print(elem.tag+": "+elem.text)

In [149]:
#Findall para encontrar un elemento específico (en este caso, el baseURL)
namespaces = {'ns': 'http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/'} # add more as needed
elementos = xmlTree.findall('.//ns:baseURL',namespaces) # aquí digo lo que estoy buscando y en qué formato de metadatos
# Imprimo el elemento que quiero en formato poco legible
print(elementos) #Element

# Imprimo en formato legible
for e in elementos:
    print("BaseURL:", e.text)

[<Element '{http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/}baseURL' at 0x7f713cd9e470>]
BaseURL: https://zenodo.org/oai2d

Listar tipos de metadatos¶

ListMetadataFormats

This verb is used to retrieve the metadata formats available from a repository. An optional argument restricts the request to the formats available for a specific item.

In [150]:
# Aquí hago lo mismo que antes:
# 1) hago una petición al servidor usando request.get() -- ahora uso el verbo ListMetadataFormats
# 2) creo que el arbol xml con ET.fromstring(oai.text)
# 3) pinto el arbol xml de manera legible, usando el iterador xmlTree.iter()

import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import requests

oai = requests.get('https://zenodo.org/oai2d?verb=ListMetadataFormats') #Peticion al servidor

#Para crear el arbol XML
xmlTree = ET.fromstring(oai.text)

iterator = xmlTree.iter()
for elem in iterator:
    print(elem.tag+": "+elem.text)

Podemos capturar sólo la información relevante

In [151]:
# aquí decido imprimir solo las informaciones que quiero:
# metadataPrefix y schema
iterator = xmlTree.iter()
for elem in iterator:
    if (elem.tag == '{http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/}metadataPrefix') or (elem.tag == '{http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/}schema'):
        print(elem.tag+": "+elem.text)

O de forma más "elegante"

In [152]:
# Todavia mejor
for e in xmlTree.findall('.//{http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/}metadataFormat'):
    metadataPrefix = e.find('{http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/}metadataPrefix').text
    schema = e.find('{http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/}schema').text
    print(metadataPrefix, ':', schema)

Podemos describir el último schema

In [153]:
# Cojo el ultimo 'schema' y hago una petición al servidor 
oai_datacite = requests.get('http://schema.datacite.org/meta/kernel-3/metadata.xsd') #Peticion al servidor
# Imprimo (no se entiende nada)
print(oai_datacite.text)

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!-- Revision history
     2010-08-26   Complete revision according to new common specification by the metadata work group after review. AJH, DTIC
	 2010-11-17 Revised to current state of kernel review, FZ, TIB 
	 2011-01-17 Complete revsion after community review. FZ, TIB
	 2011-03-17 Release of v2.1: added a namespace; mandatory properties got minLength; changes in the definitions of relationTypes
	 IsDocumentedBy/Documents and isCompiledBy/Compiles; changes type of property "Date" from xs:date to xs:string. FZ, TIB
	 2011-06-27 v2.2: namespace: kernel-2.2, additions to controlled lists "resourceType", "contributorType", "relatedIdentifierType", and "descriptionType". Removal of intermediate include-files.
     2013-05 v3.0: namespace: kernel-3.0; delete LastMetadataUpdate & MetadateVersionNumber; additions to controlled lists "contributorType", "dateType", "descriptionType", "relationType", "relatedIdentifierType" & "resourceType"; deletion of "StartDate" & "EndDate" from list "dateType" and "Film" from "resourceType";  allow arbitrary order of elements; allow optional wrapper elements to be empty; include xml:lang attribute for title, subject & description; include attribute schemeURI for nameIdentifier of creator, contributor & subject; added new attributes "relatedMetadataScheme", "schemeURI" & "schemeType" to relatedIdentifier; included new property "geoLocation" 
	 2014-08-20 v3.1: additions to controlled lists "relationType", contributorType" and "relatedIdentifierType"; introduction of new child element "affiliation" to "creator" and "contributor"-->
<xs:schema xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns="http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3" targetNamespace="http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3" elementFormDefault="qualified" xml:lang="EN">
	<xs:import namespace="http://www.w3.org/XML/1998/namespace" schemaLocation="http://www.w3.org/2009/01/xml.xsd"/>
	<xs:include schemaLocation="include/datacite-titleType-v3.xsd"/>
	<xs:include schemaLocation="include/datacite-contributorType-v3.1.xsd"/>
	<xs:include schemaLocation="include/datacite-dateType-v3.xsd"/>
	<xs:include schemaLocation="include/datacite-resourceType-v3.xsd"/>
	<xs:include schemaLocation="include/datacite-relationType-v3.1.xsd"/>
	<xs:include schemaLocation="include/datacite-relatedIdentifierType-v3.1.xsd"/>
	<xs:include schemaLocation="include/datacite-descriptionType-v3.xsd"/>
	<xs:element name="resource">
		<xs:annotation>
			<xs:documentation>
	Root element of a single record. This wrapper element is for XML implementation only and is not defined in the DataCite DOI standard.
        Note: This is the case for all wrapper elements within this schema!</xs:documentation>
			<xs:documentation>No content in this wrapper element.</xs:documentation>
		</xs:annotation>
		<xs:complexType>
			<xs:all>
				<!--REQUIRED FIELDS-->
				<xs:element name="identifier">
					<xs:annotation>
						<xs:documentation>A persistent identifier that identifies a resource.</xs:documentation>
						<xs:documentation>Currently, only DOI is allowed.</xs:documentation>
					</xs:annotation>
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:simpleContent>
							<xs:extension base="doiType">
								<xs:attribute name="identifierType" use="required" fixed="DOI"/>
							</xs:extension>
						</xs:simpleContent>
					</xs:complexType>
				</xs:element>
				<xs:element name="creators">
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:sequence>
							<xs:element name="creator" maxOccurs="unbounded">
								<xs:annotation>
									<xs:documentation>The main researchers involved working on the data, or the authors of the publication in priority order. May be a corporate/institutional or personal name.</xs:documentation>
									<xs:documentation>Format: Family, Given.</xs:documentation>
								</xs:annotation>
								<xs:complexType>
									<xs:sequence>
										<xs:element name="creatorName">
											<xs:simpleType>
												<xs:restriction base="nonemptycontentStringType"/>
											</xs:simpleType>
										</xs:element>
										<xs:element name="nameIdentifier" minOccurs="0">
											<xs:complexType>
												<xs:simpleContent>
													<xs:extension base="nonemptycontentStringType">
														<xs:attribute name="nameIdentifierScheme" use="required"/>
														<xs:attribute name="schemeURI" type="xs:anyURI" use="optional"/>
													</xs:extension>
												</xs:simpleContent>
											</xs:complexType>
										</xs:element>
										<xs:element name="affiliation" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
									</xs:sequence>
								</xs:complexType>
							</xs:element>
						</xs:sequence>
					</xs:complexType>
				</xs:element>
				<xs:element name="titles">
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:sequence>
							<xs:element name="title" maxOccurs="unbounded">
								<xs:annotation>
									<xs:documentation>A name or title by which a resource is known.</xs:documentation>
								</xs:annotation>
								<xs:complexType>
									<xs:simpleContent>
										<xs:extension base="nonemptycontentStringType">
											<xs:attribute name="titleType" type="titleType" use="optional"/>
											<xs:attribute ref="xml:lang"/>
										</xs:extension>
									</xs:simpleContent>
								</xs:complexType>
							</xs:element>
						</xs:sequence>
					</xs:complexType>
				</xs:element>
				<xs:element name="publisher">
					<xs:annotation>
						<xs:documentation>The name of the entity that holds, archives, publishes prints, distributes, releases, issues, or produces the resource. This property will be used to formulate the citation, so consider the prominence of the role.</xs:documentation>
						<xs:documentation>In the case of datasets, "publish" is understood to mean making the data available to the community of researchers.</xs:documentation>
					</xs:annotation>
					<xs:simpleType>
						<xs:restriction base="nonemptycontentStringType"/>
					</xs:simpleType>
				</xs:element>
				<xs:element name="publicationYear">
					<xs:annotation>
						<xs:documentation>Year when the data is made publicly available. If an embargo period has been in effect, use the date when the embargo period ends.</xs:documentation>
						<xs:documentation>In the case of datasets, "publish" is understood to mean making the data available on a specific date to the community of researchers. If there is no standard publication year value, use the date that would be preferred from a citation perspective.</xs:documentation>
						<xs:documentation>YYYY</xs:documentation>
					</xs:annotation>
					<xs:simpleType>
						<xs:restriction base="yearType"/>
					</xs:simpleType>
				</xs:element>
				<!--OPTIONAL FIELDS-->
				<xs:element name="subjects" minOccurs="0">
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:sequence>
							<xs:element name="subject" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
								<xs:annotation>
									<xs:documentation>Subject, keywords, classification codes, or key phrases describing the resource.</xs:documentation>
								</xs:annotation>
								<xs:complexType>
									<xs:simpleContent>
										<xs:extension base="xs:string">
											<xs:attribute name="subjectScheme" use="optional"/>
											<xs:attribute name="schemeURI" type="xs:anyURI" use="optional"/>
											<xs:attribute ref="xml:lang"/>
										</xs:extension>
									</xs:simpleContent>
								</xs:complexType>
							</xs:element>
						</xs:sequence>
					</xs:complexType>
				</xs:element>
				<xs:element name="contributors" minOccurs="0">
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:sequence>
							<xs:element name="contributor" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
								<xs:annotation>
									<xs:documentation>The institution or person responsible for collecting, creating, or otherwise contributing to the developement of the dataset.</xs:documentation>
									<xs:documentation>The personal name format should be: Family, Given.</xs:documentation>
								</xs:annotation>
								<xs:complexType>
									<xs:sequence>
										<xs:element name="contributorName">
											<xs:simpleType>
												<xs:restriction base="xs:string">
													<xs:minLength value="1"/>
												</xs:restriction>
											</xs:simpleType>
										</xs:element>
										<xs:element name="nameIdentifier" minOccurs="0">

														<xs:attribute name="nameIdentifierScheme" use="required"/>

													</xs:extension>
												</xs:simpleContent>
											</xs:complexType>

						</xs:sequence>

				<xs:element name="dates" minOccurs="0">
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:sequence>
							<xs:element name="date" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
								<xs:annotation>
									<xs:documentation>Different dates relevant to the work.</xs:documentation>
									<xs:documentation>YYYY,YYYY-MM-DD, YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ssTZD or any other format or level of granularity described in W3CDTF. Use RKMS-ISO8601 standard for depicting date ranges.</xs:documentation>

					<xs:annotation>
						<xs:documentation>Primary language of the resource. Allowed values are taken from  IETF BCP 47, ISO 639-1 language codes.</xs:documentation>
					</xs:annotation>
				</xs:element>
				<xs:element name="resourceType" minOccurs="0">
					<xs:annotation>
						<xs:documentation>The type of a resource. You may enter an additional free text description.</xs:documentation>
						<xs:documentation>The format is open, but the preferred format is a single term of some detail so that a pair can be formed with the sub-property.</xs:documentation>
					</xs:annotation>
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:simpleContent>
							<xs:extension base="xs:string">
								<xs:attribute name="resourceTypeGeneral" type="resourceType" use="required"/>
							</xs:extension>
						</xs:simpleContent>
					</xs:complexType>
				</xs:element>
				<xs:element name="alternateIdentifiers" minOccurs="0">
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:sequence>
							<xs:element name="alternateIdentifier" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
								<xs:annotation>
									<xs:documentation>An identifier or identifiers other than the primary Identifier applied to the resource being registered. This may be any alphanumeric string which is unique within its domain of issue. May be used for local identifiers. AlternateIdentifier should be used for another identifier of the same instance (same location, same file).</xs:documentation>
								</xs:annotation>
								<xs:complexType>
									<xs:simpleContent>
										<xs:extension base="xs:string">
											<xs:attribute name="alternateIdentifierType" use="required"/>
										</xs:extension>
									</xs:simpleContent>
								</xs:complexType>
							</xs:element>
						</xs:sequence>
					</xs:complexType>
				</xs:element>
				<xs:element name="relatedIdentifiers" minOccurs="0">
					<xs:complexType>
						<xs:sequence>

			<xs:pattern value="10\..+/.+"/>

		</xs:restriction>
	</xs:simpleType>

		<xs:attribute name="nameIdentifier" type="xs:string" use="optional"/>
		<xs:attribute name="nameIdentifierScheme" type="xs:string" use="optional"/>
	</xs:attributeGroup>
	<!-- defines the value for a year -->
	<xs:simpleType name="yearType">
		<xs:restriction base="xs:token">
			<xs:pattern value="[\d]{4}"/>
		</xs:restriction>
		<!-- definitions for geoLocation -->
	</xs:simpleType>
	<xs:simpleType name="point">
		<xs:restriction base="listOfDoubles">
			<xs:minLength value="2"/>
			<xs:maxLength value="2"/>
		</xs:restriction>
	</xs:simpleType>
	<xs:simpleType name="box">
		<xs:restriction base="listOfDoubles">
			<xs:minLength value="4"/>
			<xs:maxLength value="4"/>
		</xs:restriction>
	</xs:simpleType>
	<xs:simpleType name="listOfDoubles">
		<xs:list itemType="xs:double"/>
	</xs:simpleType>
</xs:schema>

namespaces = {'xs' : 'http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema'}
for tags in xmlTree.findall('.//xs:element',namespaces):
    print ('Metadato: ',tags.attrib['name'])

ListIdentifiers¶

This verb is an abbreviated form of ListRecords, retrieving only headers rather than records. Optional arguments permit selective harvesting of headers based on set membership and/or datestamp. Depending on the repository's support for deletions, a returned header may have a status attribute of "deleted" if a record matching the arguments specified in the request has been deleted.

Devuelve la cabecera de los registros, para conocer la información esencial.

Necesita el prefijo del formato de metadatos

In [156]:
# pongo verbo y prefijo

# verbo: ListIdentifiers (verb=ListIdentifiers)
# prefijo: oai_datacite  (metadataPrefix=oai_datacite)

# empiezo con un '?'
# junto los dos con una '&'

oai = requests.get('https://zenodo.org/oai2d?verb=ListIdentifiers&metadataPrefix=oai_datacite')
xmlTree = ET.fromstring(oai.text)

iterator = xmlTree.iter()
for elem in iterator:
    print(elem.tag+": "+elem.text) #Identifiers are really important because they are used to ask more information

ListRecords¶

Listar los registros

This verb is used to harvest records from a repository. Optional arguments permit selective harvesting of records based on set membership and/or datestamp. Depending on the repository's support for deletions, a returned header may have a status attribute of "deleted" if a record matching the arguments specified in the request has been deleted. No metadata will be present for records with deleted status.

In [157]:
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import requests

oai = requests.get('https://zenodo.org/oai2d?verb=ListRecords&metadataPrefix=oai_datacite')
xmlTree = ET.fromstring(oai.text)
iterator = xmlTree.iter()
for elem in iterator:
    print(elem.tag)
    print(elem.text)

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p>NCMRWF's in-house development pleased to release UMRider's next operational release <strong>v1.0.2</strong> by focusing on NCUM ensembles post production along with other few new support.</p>

<p><a href="https://zenodo.org/badge/latestdoi/20796/NCMRWF/UMRider"></a></p>


<a class="anchor" href="#what-is-new-"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>what is new ?

<ul>
<li>Bugs fix</li>
<li>12 extra user arguments features</li>
<li>New extra vars </li>
<li>checkout the <a href="https://github.com/NCMRWF/UMRider/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md#v102-2016-06-14">changlogs</a> and <a href="https://github.com/NCMRWF/UMRider/issues?q=milestone%3Av1.0.2+is%3Aclosed">milestone</a> of v1.0.2</li>
<li>This v1.0.2 mainly target the following post productions along with the existing v1.0.1 supports

<ul>
<li><strong>NCUM EPS Global Post Production</strong></li>
<li><strong>NCUM Tropical Cyclone Tracker input Production</strong></li>
<li><strong>NCUM Regional Model Wind Energy Input Production</strong></li>
<li><strong>NCUM Global Solar Energy Input Production</strong></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Existing <em>v1.0.1</em> supports

<ul>
<li>NCUM Indian Region Post Production</li>
<li>NCUM Global OSF Model Input Production</li>
<li>NCUM Global HYCOM Model Input Production </li>
<li>NCUM VSDB Input Production</li>
<li>NCUM IMD MFI Input Production</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>


<a class="anchor" href="#v102-supports"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>v1.0.2 supports

<ul>
<li>
<p>In this version v1.0.2 user will be able to control the following 37 arguments by exporting setup.cfg file into their environment variable called <strong>UMRIDER_SETUP</strong>. New arguments in this release are highlighted with bold. </p>

<ul>
<li><strong>UMtype</strong></li>
<li><strong>UMInAnlFiles</strong></li>
<li><strong>UMInShortFcstFiles</strong></li>
<li>
<strong>UMInLongFcstFiles</strong>,<br>
</li>
<li>inPath</li>
<li>outPath</li>
<li>tmpPath</li>
<li> anl_step_hour</li>
<li><strong>anl_aavars_reference_time</strong></li>
<li><strong>anl_aavars_time_bounds</strong></li>
<li><strong>fcst_step_hour</strong></li>
<li><strong>start_long_fcst_hour</strong></li>
<li><strong>end_long_fcst_hours_at_00z</strong></li>
<li><strong>end_long_fcst_hours_at_12z</strong></li>
<li>latitude</li>
<li>longitude</li>
<li>targetGridResolution</li>
<li><strong>targetGridFile</strong></li>
<li><strong>extraPolateMethod</strong></li>
<li>pressureLevels</li>
<li><strong>fillFullyMaskedVars</strong></li>
<li><strong>soilFirstSecondFixedSurfaceUnit</strong></li>
<li>startdate</li>
<li>enddate</li>
<li>loadg2utils</li>
<li>overwriteFiles</li>
<li>anlOutGrib2FilesNameStructure</li>
<li>fcstOutGrib2FilesNameStructure</li>
<li>createGrib2CtlIdxFiles</li>
<li>convertGrib2FilestoGrib1Files</li>
<li>grib1FilesNameSuffix</li>
<li>removeGrib2FilesAfterGrib1FilesCreated</li>
<li>createGrib1CtlIdxFiles</li>
<li>debug </li>
<li>setGrib2TableParameters</li>
<li><strong>wgrib2Arguments</strong></li>
<li>callBackScript</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>Also in this version v1.0.2 user will be able to control the variables by exporting vars.cfg file into their environment variable called <strong>UMRIDER_VARS</strong> . User defined variables and ordered will be retained in the out grib2 files (but pressure level variables comes first and followed by non-pressure level variables)</p></li>
<li><p>User will be able to control would they like to get 1-hourly or 3-hourly or 6-hourly or 24-hourly <strong>analysis</strong> and/or <strong>forecast</strong> files. (Note that NCUM model produces every 3-hourly instantaneous/ average/ accumulated data. Depends upon user choice it will be  instantaneous or accumulated or averaged properly)</p></li>
<li>
<p>This v1.0.2 supports for </p>

<ul>
<li><strong>NCUM EPS Global Post Production</strong></li>
<li><strong>NCUM Tropical Cyclone Tracker input Production</strong></li>
<li><strong>NCUM Regional Model Wind Energy Input Production</strong></li>
<li><strong>NCUM Global Solar Energy Input Production</strong></li>
<li>NCUM Global Post Production</li>
<li>NCUM Indian Region Post Production</li>
<li>NCUM Global OSF Model Input Production</li>
<li>NCUM Global HYCOM Model Input Production </li>
<li>NCUM VSDB Input Production</li>
<li>NCUM IMD MFI Input Production</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<p>Regards,</p>

<p>Arulalan.T</p>

<p>This is additional material for a publication (to appear) on effects of gender in the publication patterns in mathematics. Since the original data set contained no information on the authors&#39; gender, we used a publicly available annotated collection of first names to assign a binary gender. The document shows the corresponding&nbsp; algorithmic procedure that we implemented.</p>

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p>(this is the original uploaded data; there is identical set of data uploaded using zenodo GitHub integration feature, https://zenodo.org/record/51140)</p>

<p>This repository is associated with the following publication:<br />
-----------</p>

<p>Neurophysiological analytics for all!&nbsp; Free open-source software tools for documenting, analyzing, visualizing, and sharing using electronic notebooks. *Journal of Neurophysiology* 2016 Apr 20:jn.00137.2016. doi: 10.1152/jn.00137.2016.</p>

<p>https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27098025<br />
-----------</p>

<p>Please see the above report for information on the notebooks and data. A temporary executable environment with working Jupyter notebooks can be initiated by clicking the Binder link in the GitHub repository</p>

<p>https://github.com/cchorn/Neurophysiological-Analytics-for-All</p>

<p>This work was supported by the National Institutes of Health (NIH), including the Stimulating Peripheral Activity to Relieve Conditions (SPARC) Program (award# U18EB021772) and a grant to the University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute (award# P30CA047904, Cancer Center Support Grant).</p>

<p>Usage Notes:<br />
* Running the Jupyter notebooks will produce output files, including images, analyzed data, and shareable HTML copies of the notebooks, which are accessible by going to &quot;Open ...&quot; on the Jupyter File menu.<br />
* The spike sorting notebook needs to be run before the spike train notebook, which depends on a spike timestamp output file.<br />
* For offline file usage, Python and R dependencies are listed in the README documents in the Supplement folders. &nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p>The intent of this macro was to measure the thickness of collagen forming around a polymer implant stained with picrosirius red.</p>

<p>Steps:
1) User uses line tool to mark the top edge of the polymer.
2) User uses line tool to mark the top edge of the birefringent PSR stained collagen (polarized light).
3) Macro measures the perpendicular distance from line 1 to line 2 and records the distance.
4) Macro repeats measurement for every pixel along line 1 (user defined) until it reaches the end of the line.
5) Recorded measurements are shown immediately after the macro finishes.</p>

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<a class="anchor" href="#predominantmelodymakam"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>predominantmelodymakam

<p>Predominant melody extraction for makam music</p>

<p>This repository hosts the the implementation of the predominant melody extraction proposed for makam music in:</p>

<p><em>Atlı, H. S., Uyar, B., Şentürk, S., Bozkurt, B., and Serra, X. (2014). Audio feature extraction for exploring Turkish makam music. In Proceedings of 3rd International Conference on Audio Technologies for Music and Media, pages 142–153, Ankara, Turkey.</em></p>

<p>If you are using this extractor please cite the above paper. </p>

<p>The extractor is based on the methodology by [2]. The contour selection step in [2] is trained on the specfic characteristics of Western pop music and jazz. We remove this step and use a simplified contour selection step by selecting the longest contour at each time instance and discarding all other contours. Then we use the method proposed in [3] to remove the erroneous pitch estimations and correct octave errors.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#usage"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Usage

<div class="highlight highlight-source-python"><span class="pl-k">from</span> predominantmelodymakam.predominantmelodymakam <span class="pl-k">import</span> PredominantMelodyMakam
extractor <span class="pl-k">=</span> PredominantMelodyMakam()
results <span class="pl-k">=</span> extractor.run(audiofile)</div>

<p>Please refer to demo.ipynb for an interactive demo.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#installation"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Installation

<p>If you want to install the repository, it is recommended to install the package and dependencies into a virtualenv. In the terminal, do the following:</p>

virtualenv env
source env/bin/activate
python setup.py install


<p>If you want to be able to edit files and have the changes be reflected, then install the repo like this instead:</p>

pip install -e .


<p>The algorithm uses several modules in Essentia. Follow the <a href="essentia.upf.edu/documentation/installing.html">instructions</a> to install the library. Then you should link the python bindings of Essentia in the virtual environment:</p>

ln -s /usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/essentia env/lib/python2.7/site-packages



<a class="anchor" href="#changelog"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Changelog

<ul>
<li>Added the <a href="https://github.com/hsercanatli/pitchfilter">pitchfilter</a> repository as a fallback if the Essetian PitchFilter does not work due to Essentia version problem (e.g. the official version for Ubuntu 14.04).</li>
<li>Added flake8 checking to Travis CI</li>
</ul>

<a class="anchor" href="#ahenkidentifier"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>ahenkidentifier

<p>Identifies the ahenk (transposition) of a makam music recording given the tonic frequency and the symbol (or the makam)</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#usage"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Usage

<div class="highlight highlight-source-python"><span class="pl-k">from</span> ahenkidentifier.AhenkIdentifier <span class="pl-k">import</span> AhenkIdentifier

ahenk <span class="pl-k">=</span> AhenkIdentifier.identify(tonic_freq, makam)
<span class="pl-c"># or </span>
ahenk <span class="pl-k">=</span> AhenkIdentifier.identify(tonic_freq, tonic_symbol)</div>

<p>The inputs are:</p>

<div class="highlight highlight-source-python"><span class="pl-c"># tonic_freq        :   The frequency of the tonic in Hz.</span>
<span class="pl-c"># makam/tonic_symbol:   The algorithm can either accept the makam-slug or </span>
<span class="pl-c">#                       the note symbol of the tonic in SymbTr format as a string (e.g. B4b1).</span></div>

<p>For the makam-slug names, check the json file in the data folder. The slugs are the same with the ones in the filenames of the scores in the <a href="https://github.com/MTG/SymbTr">SymbTr</a> collection. The tonic symbols are notated as [Note pitch-class][Octave](Accidental Symbol(Holderian Comma)), e.g. B4b1</p>

<p>The output is:</p>

<div class="highlight highlight-source-python"><span class="pl-c"># ahenk           : The name of the ahenk as a unicode string and a dictionary of computed stats</span></div>

<p>Please refer to <a href="https://github.com/sertansenturk/ahenkidentifier/blob/master/demo.ipynb">demo.ipynb</a> for an interactive demo.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#installation"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Installation

<p>If you want to install ahenkidentifier, it is recommended to install the package and dependencies into a virtualenv. In the terminal, do the following:</p>

virtualenv env
source env/bin/activate
python setup.py install


<p>If you want to be able to edit files and have the changes be reflected, then install the repository like this instead:</p>

pip install -e .



<a class="anchor" href="#changelog"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Changelog

<ul>
<li>Added more unittests</li>
<li>Code coverage integration</li>
<li>Code climate integration</li>
</ul>


<a class="anchor" href="#issues"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Issues

<p>The &quot;Bolahenk Nısfiye&quot; ahenk, which is an octave higher than the default ahenk (&quot;Bolahenk&quot;), is omitted. In solo performances, automatic identification of this ahenk requires the frequency range of the instrument being performed. Moreover, it is ambiguous to distinguish it from &quot;Bolahenk&quot; in multi-instrument recordings.</p>

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<a class="anchor" href="#alignednotemodels"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>alignednotemodels

<p>Python tools to compute note models from note-level audio-score alignment.</p>

<p>Currently the algorithm computes the stable pitch and a pitchdistribution of each aligned note.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#usage"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Usage

<div class="highlight highlight-source-python"><span class="pl-k">from</span> alignednotemodel.AlignedNoteModel <span class="pl-k">import</span> AlignedNoteModel
alignedNoteModel <span class="pl-k">=</span> AlignedNoteModel(<span class="pl-v">kernel_width</span><span class="pl-k">=</span><span class="pl-c1">7.5</span>, <span class="pl-v">step_size</span><span class="pl-k">=</span><span class="pl-c1">7.5</span>, <span class="pl-v">pitch_threshold</span><span class="pl-k">=</span><span class="pl-c1">50</span>)

noteModels, pitchDistibution, newTonic <span class="pl-k">=</span> alignedNoteModel.get_models(pitch, alignednotes,
    tonicSymbol)</div>

<p>Instantiation parameters are:</p>

<div class="highlight highlight-source-python"><span class="pl-c"># kernel_width    : The width of the Gaussian kernel used to compute the pitch distribution </span>
<span class="pl-c">#                   (default: 7.5 cent ~ 1/3 Hc)</span>
<span class="pl-c"># step_size       : The step size between each bin of the pitch distribution (default: 7.5 cent </span>
<span class="pl-c">#                   ~ 1/3 Hc)</span>
<span class="pl-c"># pitch_threshold : Max cent difference for two pitch calues to be considered close. Used in</span>
<span class="pl-c">#                   stable pitch computation (default: 50 cent, a quarter tone)</span></div>

<p>The inputs for the get_models method are:</p>

<div class="highlight highlight-source-python"><span class="pl-c"># pitch           : an n-by-2 matrix, where the values in the first column are </span>
<span class="pl-c">#                   the timestamps and the values in the second column are frequency </span>
<span class="pl-c">#                   values</span>
<span class="pl-c"># alignednotes    : the list of aligned notes. This is read from the alignedNotes.json </span>
<span class="pl-c">#                   output from the fragmentLinker (https://github.com/sertansenturk/fragmentLinker) </span>
<span class="pl-c">#                   repository </span>
<span class="pl-c"># tonicsymbol     : The tonic symbol in the symbTr format (e.g. B4b1)</span></div>

<p>The outputs are:</p>

<div class="highlight highlight-source-python"><span class="pl-c"># noteModels        : The model for each note symbol</span>
<span class="pl-c"># pitchDistribution : The pitch distribution computed from the pitch input</span>
<span class="pl-c"># newtonic          : The updated tonic according to the note model of the tonic symbol</span></div>


<a class="anchor" href="#installation"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Installation

<p>If you want to install the repository, it is recommended to install the package and dependencies into a virtualenv. In the terminal, do the following:</p>

virtualenv env
source env/bin/activate
python setup.py install


<p>If you want to be able to edit files and have the changes be reflected, then
install the repository like this instead</p>

pip install -e .


<p>The algorithm uses several modules in Essentia. Follow the <a href="essentia.upf.edu/documentation/installing.html">instructions</a> to install the library.</p>

<p>Now you can install the rest of the dependencies:</p>

pip install -r requirements

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p><strong>This release requires an update to the config file in PEcAn web interface. Without this change the web interface will not work. See config.php changes.</strong></p>

<p>Following are the major new features of this release. Besides these new features many bugs have been fixed, see <a href="https://github.com/PecanProject/pecan/issues?q=milestone%3A%221.4.5%3A+CRUNCEP%2C+Preles%22+is%3Aclosed">milestone 1.4.5</a> list of issues or <a href="https://github.com/PecanProject/pecan/compare/v1.4.4...v1.4.5">complete list of commits</a>.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#new-models"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>New Models

<p>This release now adds support for the PRELES model.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#preles"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>PRELES

<p>The PREdiction of Light use efficiency, Evapotranspiration, and Soil water (PRELES)  model was developed by  a team at the Natural Resources Institute Finland with the goal to &quot;develop a semi-empirical, intermediate-complexity model of evapotranspiration and its coupling with canopy photosynthesis&quot; (Peltoniemi et al 2015). Calibrated for boreal regions, it uses common meteorological drivers (temperature, pressure, precipitation, photosynthetically active radiation, and CO2) to predict GPP and water balance (soil water, evaporation, and transpiration). It offers comparatively quick analyses, due to its parsimonious code, making it a unique choice among our suite of model options.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#new-met-data"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>New Met Data

<p>This release adds support for CRUNCEP</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#cruncep"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>CRUNCEP

<p>Add some text here about CRUNCEP, where it comes from etc.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#web-interface"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Web Interface

<p>The web interface now allows the user to login using their credentials, event if the flag authorization required is not set. Any run started when logged in will be recorded as belonging to the logged in user. Only users logged in can now delete workflows.</p>

<p>Users can now filter the history page, by their own runs, those that are available locally, succeeded and by textual search (in notes, model, site).</p>

<p>Notes are no longer an advanced feature, but can now be added during the input section.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#configphp-changes"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>config.php changes

<p>A major change has been done to the web interface configuration files. Please make sure to update your config.php, without these changes your web interface will not allow you to do any runs!</p>

<p>The variables $hostlist, $qsuboptions and $qsublist have been merged into a single variable called $hostlist. This list has a list of all hosts that are shown in the host pull down list, as well as any options for qsub. This now also allows you to specify a folder on the remote system to use. All runs will use this remote folder! Please see the <a href="https://github.com/PecanProject/pecan/blob/master/web/config.example.php">example.config.php</a></p>

<p>The following variables are no longer used : $qsuboptions, $qsublist, $ed_soil, $ed_inputs and can be safely removed from you config.php (after fixing the above).</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#additional-changes"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Additional changes

<p>PEcAn now leverages of <a href="https://travis-ci.org/PecanProject/pecan">Travis CI</a> for continuous integration. To use this in your own branches and forks of PEcAn make sure you have merged in the master branch from PEcAn and created an account on <a href="https://travis-ci.org/">Travis CI</a>. Once that is done you should be able to flip the switch for PEcAn and it will start to build automatically anytime you push changes to your branches/fork.</p>

<p>This patch also marks a change to documentation. We have migrated our github wiki to <a href="https://www.gitbook.com/book/pecan/pecan-documentation/details">gitbook</a> and will no longer update the wiki on github. It will allow for easier exportation of PecAn documentation (pdf,epub,  mobi, web) as well as make it easier to gain feedback from users (inline commenting). </p>


<a class="anchor" href="#downloads"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Downloads

<p>The latest version of the VM can be downloaded from <a href="http://opensource.ncsa.illinois.edu/projects/artifacts.php?key=PECAN&version=1.4.5">NCSA</a></p>

<a class="anchor" href="#first-release-of-elf_analyserandplot"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>First release of ELF_AnalyserAndPlot

<p><em>This program plots on a graph the electronic variations around the atoms along an IRC calculation of a chemical reaction.  From the out files generated by ELF calculation, that contain information about geometry, basin and values of them.</em></p>


<a class="anchor" href="#features"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a><em>Features:</em>


<ul>
<li>Extract geometry of atoms and basins from the out-files generated;</li>
<li>Extract values for each basin;</li>
<li>Create association between basin/s and atom/s;</li>
<li>Divide in different files the interactions between atoms and values in each point;</li>
<li>Clean useless interaction (the ones that don't suffer variations);</li>
<li>Plot with lines the values in a graph, giving different options about the elaboration.</li>
</ul>


<a class="anchor" href="#how-to-install"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a><em>How to install:</em>


Use the installer &quot;install.sh&quot; and follow the instruction.


<p>For manual installation create a folder, paste inside all files and create an alias that executes &quot;<em>main.sh</em>&quot; 
from that folder then insert an environmental variable writing: <em>export EAAPpath=&quot;here the path where find files&quot;</em>. 
Anyway, you can find more informations reading inside <em>install.sh</em>.</p>


<a class="anchor" href="#how-to-use"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a><em>How to use:</em>


Run the alias you setted up (whether you used the automatic installer or you did it manually)
into a folder that contains the out-files generated from ELF calculation.


<p>The <em>name</em> of the file have to be with a part of your choosing, after this a <em>dash</em> and the progressive <em>number</em>
from 1 to the last step (without interruptions) and after the number an <em>underscore</em> and the word &quot;<em>elf</em>&quot;</p>

<p><strong>example:</strong> &quot;name you prefer&quot;-&quot;number&quot;_elf.out</p>

<ul>
<li>
<p>Data mappings:</p>

<ul>
<li>#45: <strong>Changed DataMappings remoteInput/Output from records to <em>simple Maps</em></strong>
</li>
<li>Added an option to the config to switch on/off input objects existence check</li>
<li>#44: Renamed DataMapping's id to label</li>
<li>#47: Added a logger message and some kind of progress output for the input objects existence check</li>
<li>#50: Instead of checking input objects object metadata, listing objects with the given prefix</li>
<li>#52: Added a check for missing/non-needed input/output data keys in the datamappings</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p>Data processing:</p>

<ul>
<li>#51: Fixed input objects handling by passing the map of (dataKey.label -&gt; fileLocation) from worker to the processing context; this way context.inputFile lookup doesn't rely on conventions and return the actual file location</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p>Self-termination:</p>

<ul>
<li>#48: Added a time deadline for SQS polling</li>
<li>Added some logging and exception handling to the polling</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p>Other fixes:</p>

<ul>
<li>#49: Removed any worker instance state tagging for now; was causing RequestLimitExceeded on a big autoscaling group with quick tasks</li>
<li>#43: Changed log messages for downloads/uploads</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<p>Supplementary download files for the Journal Of Chemical Physics&nbsp;</p>

<p>Manuscript Number A16.01.0139</p>

<p>Title: The Near-IR Spectrum of NO(\tilde{X}2&Pi;)-Ne Detected Through Excitation Into the A-State Continuum: A joint Experimental and Theoretical Study&nbsp;</p>

<p>Author(s): Jacek Klos, Susannah Zhang, and Henning Meyer&nbsp;</p>

<p>Filenames:&nbsp;<br />
pot_nenox_v0_klos.f&nbsp;<br />
pot_nenox_v2_klos.f</p>

<p>These are Hibridon (http://www2.chem.umd.edu/groups/alexander/hibridon/hib43/hibhelp.html) potential files<br />
for Ne-NO(X) diabatic Vsum and Vdif potentials averaged over v=0 of NO(X) (pot_nenox_v0_klos.f) and v=2 of NO(X) (pot_nenox_v2_klos.f).&nbsp;</p>
{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
PESs in routines form for  Hibridon scattering program.

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
Added
<ul>
<li>possible to specify options that are common to all stimuli in [GENERAL] section
of config.ini file<ul>
<li>e.g., image_size, item_bbox_size, jitter, grid_size</li>
<li>if one of these options is also specified in a section for a specific stimulus,
that value overrides the one specified in the general section</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
Changed
<ul>
<li>user specifies an item bounding box for items in stimulus, instead of 'rect'<ul>
<li>the actual item is drawn within this "bounding box"</li>
<li>would make it possible to draw items with different sizes but same shape</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>user specifies sizes in order of (height, width)<ul>
<li>since people feeding images to neural networks are used to this order</li>
<li>even though PyGame expects (width, height)</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<p>
The gCube System - gCube Ckan metadata publisher widget<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
gCube Ckan metadata publisher widget is a GWT Widget that allows to publish metadata on the d4science ckan data catalogue.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Version<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
1.3.1-4.7.1-152460 (2017-10-19)<br>
 <br>
Please see the file named "changelog.xml" in this directory for the release notes.<br>
 <br>
 <br>

--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>

<p>
The gCube System - Tabular Data SQL Evaluator<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
Component of Tabular Data that allows to transform a tabular data expressions into a SQL WHERE clause statement<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>

--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>

open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>

by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>

239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>

<p>
The gCube System - Geo Explorer Portlet<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
The Geo Explorer Portlet lets the users discovery and analize OGC layers from more server sources.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Version<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
2.11.0-4.7.1-150647 (2017-10-19)<br>
 <br>
Please see the file named "changelog.xml" in this directory for the release notes.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Authors<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
* Francesco Mangiacrapa (francesco.mangiacrapa-AT-isti.cnr.it), Istituto di Scienza e Tecnologie dell'Informazione "A. Faedo" - CNR, Pisa (Italy). <br>
 <br>
Maintainers<br>
-----------<br>
 <br>
* Francesco Mangiacrapa (francesco.mangiacrapa-AT-isti.cnr.it), Istituto di Scienza e Tecnologie dell'Informazione "A. Faedo" - CNR, Pisa (Italy). <br>

<p>
The gCube System - Top Topics Portlet<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
Top Topics Portlet shows the top topics in the scope where is deployed.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Version<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
2.1.0-4.7.1-134465 (2017-10-19)<br>
 <br>
Please see the file named "changelog.xml" in this directory for the release notes.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Authors<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
* Massimiliano Assante (massimiliano.assante@isti.cnr.it), Istituto di Scienza e Tecnologie dell'Informazione "A. Faedo" - CNR, Pisa (Italy).<br>
 <br>
Maintainers<br>
-----------<br>
 <br>
* Massimiliano Assante (massimiliano.assante@isti.cnr.it), Istituto di Scienza e Tecnologie dell'Informazione "A. Faedo" - CNR, Pisa (Italy).<br>
 <br>

    http://svn.research-infrastructures.eu/public/d4science/gcube/trunk/portlets/user/top-topics<br>
 <br>
Binaries can be downloaded from the gCube website: <br>
   https://www.gcube-system.org/<br>
 <br>
 <br>

Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>

<p>
The gCube System - ldap-export-servlet Maven Webapp<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
This component read periodically exports users and their groups in LDAP<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Version<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
1.2.0-4.7.0-131877 (2017-10-13)<br>
 <br>
Please see the file named "changelog.xml" in this directory for the release notes.<br>
 <br>
 <br>

--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
* Massimiliano Assante (massimiliano.assante-AT-isti.cnr.it), Istituto di Scienza e Tecnologie dell'Informazione "A. Faedo" - CNR, Pisa (Italy).<br>

<p>
The gCube System - species-link-spd-plugin<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
SpeciesLink Plugin<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Version<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
1.8.0-4.7.0-144167 (2017-10-12)<br>
 <br>
Please see the file named "changelog.xml" in this directory for the release notes.<br>
 <br>
 <br>

<p>
The gCube System - tabular-data-codelistmapping-import-widget<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
tabular-data-codelistmapping-import-widget allows import from url, file and workspace of maps for codelist<br>
 <br>
<br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Version<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
1.8.0-4.7.0-142617 (2017-10-13)<br>
 <br>

<p>
The gCube System - operation-view<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
TDM Module with operations concerning charts and diagram generation.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>

<p>
The gCube System - Data Management Facility Portlet<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
Data Management Facility Portlet for AquaMaps suite<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>
 <br>
 <br>

--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
1.7.4-4.7.0-131496 (2017-10-13)<br>

<p>
The gCube System - A distribution bundle for the SmartGears Framework<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
A distribution bundle for the SmartGears Framework containing Tomcat and ReadMe files to install quickly Smartgears<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>

<p>
The gCube System - Custom Portal Handler<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
gCube Custom Portal Handler is a component that all portlets need to use to set the context where they running. <br>
		It also contains utils from creating community and organization with their layouts into liferay portal.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
This software is part of the gCube Framework (https://www.gcube-system.org/): an<br>
open-source software toolkit used for building and operating Hybrid Data<br>
Infrastructures enabling the dynamic deployment of Virtual Research Environments<br>
by favouring the realisation of reuse oriented policies.<br>
 <br>
The projects leading to this software have received funding from a series of<br>
European Union programmes including:<br>
* the Sixth Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development -<br>
DILIGENT (grant no. 004260);<br>
* the Seventh Framework Programme for research, technological development and<br>
demonstration - D4Science (grant no. 212488), D4Science-II (grant no.<br>
239019),ENVRI (grant no. 283465), EUBrazilOpenBio (grant no. 288754), iMarine<br>
(grant no. 283644);<br>
* the H2020 research and innovation programme - BlueBRIDGE (grant no. 675680),<br>
EGIEngage (grant no. 654142), ENVRIplus (grant no. 654182), Parthenos (grant<br>
no. 654119), SoBigData (grant no. 654024);<br>
 <br>
 <br>
Version<br>
--------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
2.1.0-4.7.0-131316 (2017-10-12)<br>
 <br>
Please see the file named "changelog.xml" in this directory for the release notes.<br>
 <br>
 <br>

Ejercicio 1¶

Muestra sólo el identificador y las palabras clave (subject)

In [158]:
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import requests

# Hago la petición al servidor
oai = requests.get('https://zenodo.org/oai2d?verb=ListRecords&metadataPrefix=oai_datacite')

# Creo un xmlTree 
xmlTree = ET.fromstring(oai.text)

# Recorro el xmlTree:
# busco los elementos 'record'
# y los sub-elementos 'identifier' y 'subject'
records = xmlTree.findall('.//{http://www.openarchives.org/OAI/2.0/}record')
for el in records:
    for identifier in el.findall('.//{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}identifier'):
        print("Identifier:",identifier.text)
    for subject in el.findall('.//{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}subject'):          
        print("Subject:",subject.text)
    print()

import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET

bounds = "&from='2017-01-01'&until='2017-12-31'" #Para filtrar por fechas
oai = requests.get('https://zenodo.org/oai2d?verb=ListRecords&metadataPrefix=oai_datacite'+bounds)
xmlTree = ET.fromstring(oai.text)
iterator = xmlTree.iter()
for elem in iterator:
    print(elem.tag)
    print(elem.text)

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p>I made two trips to the Muangphe village of Xinfazhai, Heizhiguo Township, Guangnan County, Yunnan, China in August 2012 and April 2013. Both times, my informant was Luo Youwang 罗友旺, the mayor of Xinfazhai village. Muangphe has pharyngeal consonants like Northern Qiang, Atayal, and Amis.<br>
<br>
Muangphe (muaŋ⁵&sup3;, muaŋ⁵⁵phe&sup2;&sup1;) is spoken in 5 villages of Babao and Heizhiguo townships, with ethnic Muangphe found in a total of 7 villages. They are known locally to other ethnic groups as the Lai 俫 or Lairen 俫人, which is also applied to the Austroasiatic-speaking Bolyu located further to the north in Longlin County, Guangxi. Phonologically, Muangphe is characterized by the pre-velarization of many of its initials; this does not occur in any of the other Muangphe languages.<br>
<br>
Locals of Xinfazhai 新发寨 report that Muangphe is most vigorously spoken in their village by both adults and children, while it is spoken to a lesser extent in the four villages of Jilai 吉赖, Mudilang 木底郎, Wabiao 瓦标, and Muliang 木良. Xinfazhai locals report that the language is not being transmitted to children in, and is thus likely moribund, in those four villages. Muangphe is spoken only by very few elderly individuals in Mulou 木娄and Mulong 木聋 villages, both located in Xinjie administrative village新街村. Based on these demographics, speakers of Muangphe number at least 200 but do not exceed 1,000. It is by all means an endangered language, and is moribund in most villages except for at least Xinfazhai 新发寨.<br>
<br>
Xinfazhai locals report that their ancestors had come from a location further to the east called &ldquo;Jiangxi 江西&rdquo;. They also claim to have bronze drums inherited from their ancestors, which are maintained and kept hidden by the village elders. An ethnic Han resident of Mulang 木浪 reports watching the local Yi performing bronze drum dances a few decades ago, but says that they are no longer performed. Traditional ethnic clothing is not worn in any of the Muangphe villages.<br>
<br>
Many village names in Heizhiguo township and Babao township contain the prefix &ldquo;Mu- 木&rdquo;. This likely signifies that the village used to have, or currently has, a Mangish-speaking population, since they have autonyms prefixed maŋ- ~ muŋ-. Similarly, areas that were historically Buyang have many village suffixed &ldquo;-yang 央&rdquo; (Li Jinfang 1999).<br>
<br>
&nbsp;</p>

<p>On August 25, 2012, in Tianba, Dongdu Village, Tiechang Township, Malipo County, Yunnan, China, I interviewed a 78-year-old man named Yang Guangsheng 杨光升, whom I recorded some White Gelao words from. Yang spoke White Gelao quite fluently. He reported other White Gelao speakers as (1) Yang Guangpu 杨光甫, a White Gelao speaker in Fengyan, and (2) Yang Guangqing 杨光睛, a White Gelao speaker of Fanpo, Yangwan Township who is the brother of Yang Guangsheng 杨光升.</p>

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p>Recorded on May 7, 2015</p>

<p>This word list focuses mostly on lexical items that could potentially have initial consonant clusters.</p>

<p><br>
The road to the Kathu villages is extremely rocky, and only one driver (&ldquo;Xiaoliu&rdquo; 小刘 who was from that area himself) was willing to take me up there, out of nearly 10 different drivers who said they wouldn&#39;t take anyone up there even if they were offered 500-600 yuan. A few decades ago, Kathu children had to walk 4 hours each way to school in Nanping Town and then another 4 hours back, in addition to having to cook for themselves.<br>
<br>
Kathu speakers said their ancestors came from &ldquo;Jiangxi&rdquo; 江西.<br>
<br>
My Kathu informants were:<br>
Wang Anxing 王安兴 (M), 60<br>
Tian Huiping 田桂平 (F), 56<br>
<br>
Kathu is also spoken in Dayashao 大牙扫, which also has many Zhuang speakers, just like in Balong.<br>
<br>
The Kathu are known by many other local ethnic groups as &ldquo;Flowery Buttocks&rdquo; 花屁股.<br>
<br>
There are 3 more Kathu villages located outside Nanping Township, namely Jiala 甲腊, Jiamu 甲墓, and Bazi 坝子, which are located in Laojing Village 老井村 of Dongbao Township 董堡乡 (located on the southern banks of the Xiyang River 西洋江). They had reported migrating over from the Anwang-Balong area, and the dialect is slightly different. All children speak the language.</p>
{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
https://sites.google.com/site/msealangs/mondzish-branch/kathu

<p>On February 10, 2014 In U Nh&iacute; Chải, Dao San Township, Phong Tho District, Lai Chau Province, Vietnam, I met a &quot;Lo Lo&quot; woman who said that the autonym of her group was Nisuphu [ȵi&sup3;&sup3;so⁵⁵pʰo&sup2;&sup1;]. She was born in China, but had married into a Hani (Ha Nhi) family in U Nhi Chai. Her language turned out to be Nisu (Southern Yi), a Loloish language.</p>

<p>On February 7, 2014, I met 2 young women in their 20&#39;s named Anh H&agrave; and Thuy&ecirc;n Kim. They spoken Laopa ([lau21 pa51), which turned out to be a dialect of Laghuu (Xa Pho). The Laopa women also were highly fluent in Putonghua (standard Mandarin Chinese) and Vietnamese.</p>

<p>On April 25, 2014 in Guodazhai Township, Fengqing County, Yunnan Province, China, I collected data on Miao of Dashitouzhai 大石头寨 and Malutang 马鹿塘. The Miao there speak a form of Chuanqiandian Miao, otherwise known as Hmong. All children speak the language in Dashitouzhai and Malutang. My informant was an elderly woman who also sang some Miao folk songs for me.</p>

<p>On May 7, 2013, I visited Wantai, Daping Township, Hezhou City 贺州市大平乡万太组 (or Wantai 湾太, Longcao Village 龙曹村, Daping Township 大平瑶族乡, Hezhou City) in Guangxi, China. My informant was an elderly man named Deng Rushan 邓如山 (February 1943). He was a Mien speaking belonging to the Guoshan Yao 过山瑶 group, whom he said are also known as the Pingtou Yao 平头瑶. His ancestors had migrated from Wuguang 梧广. Deng also told me that there are Jian Yao 尖瑶 in Qingshui Village, Gonghui Township (公会镇清水村) and in Huangdong 黄洞瑶族乡.</p>

Va (Southern) audio word list

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p>On April 10-11, 2014, I collected about 270 words from Northern Va and about 100 words from Southern Va. Both are spoken in several scattered villages in Jingxing Township 景星乡, Mojiang County, Yunnan, China. Southern Va is spoken only by middle-age and elderly people, but not by children. It is more conservative and retains many sesquisyllabic prefixes, particularly /s-/, which are not retained in Northern Va. Northern Va, which is also vigorously spoken by children, may have about 2,000 speakers, and for Southern Va, perhaps just under 1,000. The Va of Mojiang County are geographically isolated from other Austroasiatic-speaking groups, as no other Austroasiatic languages are spoken within perhaps a 100-km radius.<br>
<br>
My Northern Va informant, surnamed Li 李, is a 27-year-old male shopkeeper who is fluent in Putonghua (standard Mandarin), Southwestern Mandarin, and Va. He has worked in Kunming for a few years before. According to Li, the ancestors of the Va were also called &ldquo;Mang 莽&rdquo; in the past, and had migrated from the Dali area, which is located much further to the northwest. My Southern Va informant is 42-year-old Wang Lijuan 王丽娟. Data collection on Southern Va was performed under time constraints, since it was done during a bus break by the side of a road while I was on my way to the Mojiang county seat.<br>
<br>
My Northern Va informant claimed that Southern Va is very difficult for him to understand, but my Southern Va informant reported that she understands Northern Va perfectly well. Also, speakers are aware that Va numerals (except 1-3) are from Tai. However, most of their neighbors are Kaduo (kha31 tu31) speakers, a Southern Loloish group; the Tai are a minority in the region.<br>
<br>
Northern Va is spoken in about 8 villages in Taihe Administrative Village 太和村, Jingxing Township 景星乡, Mojiang County, Yunnan, China by about 600 ethnic Bulang households or just over 2,000 families. All generations, including children, speak the language fluently.<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wamo 挖墨<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Xinzhai 新寨 (Upper 上 and Lower 下 hamlets)<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jiuzhai 旧寨<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dazhai 大寨 (Upper 上 and Lower 下 hamlets)<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Xiaozhai 小寨 (Upper 上 and Lower 下 hamlets)<br>
<br>
Southern Va is spoken in the following villages of Zhenglong Administrative Village 正龙村, Jingxing Township 景星乡, Mojiang County, Yunnan, China. The children do not speak Va.<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pingtian 平田<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Banglao 蚌老 (culture and language best preserved)<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Miena 乜那<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Binggu 丙故<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yin&rsquo;gou 阴沟<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yakou 丫口 (culture and language least preserved)<br>
<br>
Even though their autonym is &ldquo;Va,&rdquo; their language is fully Angkuic, and does not have any Waic influence or substrate.</p>
{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
https://sites.google.com/site/msealangs/austroasiatic/va

<p>On May 2, 2013, I visited two Biao Min villages of Guanyang County, Guangxi, China.</p>

<p><br>
The dialects are reported to be mutually intelligible. However, this language is undocumented, and is unintelligible with Biao Min of Dongshan Township, Quanzhou County, Guangxi located just to the north.<br>
<br>
Dialect 1:</p>

<ul>
	<li>Mifengshan 蜜蜂山, Jiangtang 江塘村, Shuiche Township 水车乡, Guanyang County</li>
</ul>

<p><br>
Dialect 2:</p>

<ul>
	<li>Baizhuping 白竹坪, Wenshi Township 文市乡, Guanyang County</li>
	<li>Xiamashan 下马山, Xieshui Village 斜水村, Dongshan Township 东山乡, Quanzhou County (reported as the same dialect by speakers in Baizhuping; I did not have a chance to visit Xiamashan)</li>
</ul>

<p>On April 20, 2013, I recorded Kathu of Anwang village 安王村, Nanping Township 南屏镇, Guangnan County, Yunnan.</p>

<p>Thou (autonym: &theta;ou⁵&sup3;) is spoken in Balong village 坝聋村, while Kathu (ka&sup3;&sup3;&theta;u&sup3;&sup3;) is spoken further downhills in Anwang village 安王村. They are known locally to other ethnic groups as the White Yi. Both administrative villages are adjacent to each other, and are administered as part of Nanping Town, Guangnan County, Yunnan.</p>

Va (Northern) audio word list

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p>On April 10-11, 2014, I collected about 270 words from Northern Va and about 100 words from Southern Va. Both are spoken in several scattered villages in Jingxing Township 景星乡, Mojiang County, Yunnan, China. Southern Va is spoken only by middle-age and elderly people, but not by children. It is more conservative and retains many sesquisyllabic prefixes, particularly /s-/, which are not retained in Northern Va. Northern Va may have about 2,000 speakers, and for Southern Va, perhaps just under 1,000. The Va of Mojiang County are geographically isolated from other Austroasiatic-speaking groups, as no other Austroasiatic languages are spoken within perhaps a 100-km radius.</p>

<p>My Northern Va informant, surnamed Li 李, is a 27-year-old male shopkeeper who is fluent in Putonghua (standard Mandarin), Southwestern Mandarin, and Va. He has worked in Kunming for a few years before. According to Li, the ancestors of the Va were also called &ldquo;Mang 莽&rdquo; in the past, and had migrated from the Dali area, which is located much further to the northwest. My Southern Va informant is 42-year-old Wang Lijuan 王丽娟. Data collection on Southern Va was performed under time constraints, since it was done during a bus break by the side of a road while I was on my way to the Mojiang county seat.<br>
<br>
My Northern Va informant claimed that Southern Va is very difficult for him to understand, but my Southern Va informant reported that she understands Northern Va perfectly well. Also, speakers are aware that Va numerals (except 1-3) are from Tai. However, most of their neighbors are Kaduo (kha31 tu31) speakers, a Southern Loloish group; the Tai are a minority in the region.<br>
<br>
Northern Va is spoken in about 8 villages in Taihe Administrative Village 太和村, Jingxing Township 景星乡, Mojiang County, Yunnan, China by about 600 ethnic Bulang households or just over 2,000 families. All generations, including children, speak the language fluently.<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wamo 挖墨<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Xinzhai 新寨 (Upper 上 and Lower 下 hamlets)<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jiuzhai 旧寨<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dazhai 大寨 (Upper 上 and Lower 下 hamlets)<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Xiaozhai 小寨 (Upper 上 and Lower 下 hamlets)<br>
<br>
Southern Va is spoken in the following villages of Zhenglong Administrative Village 正龙村, Jingxing Township 景星乡, Mojiang County, Yunnan, China. The children do not speak Va.<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pingtian 平田<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Banglao 蚌老 (culture and language best preserved)<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Miena 乜那<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Binggu 丙故<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yin&rsquo;gou 阴沟<br>
&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yakou 丫口 (culture and language least preserved)<br>
<br>
Even though their autonym is &ldquo;Va,&rdquo; their language is fully Angkuic, and does not have any Waic influence or substrate.</p>

{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
<p>Three dialects of Biao were documented from May 8-9, 2013 in:</p>

<ul>
	<li>Yonggu Township 永固镇, Huaiji County, Guangdong</li>
	<li>Zhailing Village 寨岭村, Dagang Township 大岗镇, Huaiji County, Guangdong</li>
	<li>Baoshan Village 保山村, Chang&#39;an Township 长安镇, Fengkai County, Guangdong</li>
</ul>

<p>Liang Min (2002) documented the Biao lect of Shidong Township 诗洞镇, Huaiji County, and included a few examples from Yonggu Biao. Biao of Dagang Township 大岗镇 was previously undocumented. Shidong and Yonggu Biao speakers both report each others&rsquo; lects to be unintelligible. Dagang Biao is also unintelligible with both Shidong Biao and Yonggu Biao.</p>

<p>(1) Yonggu Township 永固镇, Huaiji County, Guangdong Province<br>
(2) Zhailing Village 寨岭村, Dagang Township 大岗镇, Huaiji County, Guangdong Province</p>

<p>I have also collected data from Baoshan Village 保山村, Chang&#39;an Township 长安镇, Fengkai County, Guangdong Province. This variety turned out to be mutually intelligible with the Dagang lect, since my informant from Zhailing, Dagang was able to fully converse with the Biao speakers of Baoshan when he traveled with me to the field site. Locals in Dagang report that Biao of Liangcun Township 梁村镇 is intelligible and nearly identical with Dagang Biao. Thus, there are at least three mutually unintelligible varieties of Biao, namely (1) Shidong 诗洞, (2) Yonggu 永固, and (3) Dagang 大岗.</p>

<p>Biao appears to share some lexical and phonological links with Lakkja, which some Chinese linguists consider to be a divergent Kam-Sui language. Thus, Biao may form a subgroup with Kam-Sui and/or Lakkja, or it may even constitute a primary branch of Kra-Dai on its own.</p>
{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description
https://sites.google.com/site/msealangs/kra-dai/biao

<p>Liang Min (2002) documented the Biao lect of Shidong Township 诗洞镇, Huaiji County, and included a few examples from Yonggu Biao. Biao of Dagang Township 大岗镇 was previously undocumented. Shidong and Yonggu Biao speakers both report each others&rsquo; lects to be unintelligible. Dagang Biao is also unintelligible with both Shidong Biao and Yonggu Biao.</p>

<p>(1) Yonggu Township 永固镇, Huaiji County, Guangdong Province<br>
(2) Zhailing Village 寨岭村, Dagang Township 大岗镇, Huaiji County, Guangdong Province</p>

<p>I have also collected data from Baoshan Village 保山村, Chang&#39;an Township 长安镇, Fengkai County, Guangdong Province. This variety turned out to be mutually intelligible with the Dagang lect, since my informant from Zhailing, Dagang was able to fully converse with the Biao speakers of Baoshan when he traveled with me to the field site. Locals in Dagang report that Biao of Liangcun Township 梁村镇 is intelligible and nearly identical with Dagang Biao. Thus, there are at least three mutually unintelligible varieties of Biao, namely (1) Shidong 诗洞, (2) Yonggu 永固, and (3) Dagang 大岗.</p>

<p>Biao appears to share some lexical and phonological links with Lakkja, which some Chinese linguists consider to be a divergent Kam-Sui language. Thus, Biao may form a subgroup with Kam-Sui and/or Lakkja, or it may even constitute a primary branch of Kra-Dai on its own.</p>
{http://datacite.org/schema/kernel-3}description

<p>On April 13, 2013, I visited the ethnic &quot;Shui&quot; village of Upper Abaiji (locally called Aboji) 上阿白吉村 in Luoping County, Yunnan, China. The village was very remote, and was accessible only via a narrow footpath that was one hour&#39;s walk from the nearest paved road. I had to walk one hour there, with a local guide leading me on the path up to Aboji village.</p>

<p>My informant was a 66-year-old man named Wang Qibing 王齐兵. Wang reported that his language, which I have determined to be a Buyi dialect, was mutually intelligible with Shui of Luo&rsquo;e, Fuyuan County. Locals Han Chinese and even the Shui themselves also refer to the Shui as &ldquo;Buyi.&rdquo; Wang also reported that there are ethnic Yi in Fanai 发耐, Xinzhai 新寨, Xinfacun 新发村.</p>
